{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487038","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487038"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:55:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:55:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"238"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"238","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/238"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.79,0.06,0.08,0.04,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"238"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90542"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"238","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/238"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"238"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74767"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"272"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2666"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11104"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11208"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15230"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28920"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90542","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90542"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 33-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with sudden-onset right-sided pleuritic chest pain and severe shortness of breath following an episode of coughing. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed and is using accessory muscles to breathe. His pulse rate is 112/min, blood pressure 105/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 88% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. Cardiorespiratory examination reveals increased resonance over the right side of his chest and diminished breath sounds. A mid-systolic click is heard, accompanied by a late systolic murmur that is louder with the handgrip manoeuvre. A chest X-ray confirms a large right-sided pneumothorax (Image). The patient is given appropriate analgesia and supplemental oxygen. Needle thoracocentesis has been attempted but was unsuccessful in improving the patient\u0027s symptoms or oxygen saturation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chest drain insertion","Admission for observation with high-flow oxygen therapy","Repeat needle thoracocentesis","Pleurodesis","Echocardiogram"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical and radiological features consistent with a large right-sided pneumothorax. The patient\u0027s respiratory distress and hypoxia (SpO2 88%) indicate the need for immediate intervention, especially after an unsuccessful needle thoracocentesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChest drain insertion\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step in management for this patient. The combination of respiratory distress, hypoxia, and the size of the pneumothorax warrant immediate active intervention. Chest drain insertion is the recommended treatment for large pneumothoraces, especially when patients show signs of physiological compromise such as hypoxia, tachycardia, and respiratory distress. When needle thoracocentesis fails to improve a patient\u0027s condition, progression to chest drain insertion is the standard approach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdmission for observation with high-flow oxygen therapy\u003C/strong\u003E would be inadequate for a patient with a large pneumothorax who is hypoxic and in respiratory distress, particularly after a failed needle thoracocentesis. This conservative approach is only suitable for small, asymptomatic pneumothoraces in stable patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat needle thoracocentesis\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to be successful if the first attempt failed. Needle thoracocentesis is generally considered a temporizing measure in emergency situations, and when unsuccessful, proceeding to definitive management with a chest drain is appropriate rather than repeating the same intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPleurodesis\u003C/strong\u003E is a procedure used in the management of recurrent pneumothoraces or chronic pleural effusions. It involves obliterating the pleural space to prevent recurrence. While it may be considered in the long-term management of patients with recurrent pneumothoraces, it is not an appropriate acute management strategy for this patient\u0027s current presentation, which requires immediate decompression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEchocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E would be useful for further evaluation of the patient\u0027s cardiac findings (mid-systolic click and late systolic murmur suggestive of mitral valve prolapse). These findings could potentially indicate an underlying connective tissue disorder such as Marfan syndrome, which is a risk factor for spontaneous pneumothorax. However, addressing the acute pneumothorax takes priority over cardiac evaluation at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the priority in this case is to manage the large pneumothorax causing the patient\u0027s significant respiratory compromise. After chest drain insertion and resolution of the pneumothorax, further investigation of the cardiac findings would be appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Active intervention (chest drain insertion) is required for a large pneumothorax, especially when the patient is hypoxic or in respiratory distress.","Needle thoracocentesis may be insufficient for large pneumothoraces and should be followed by definitive chest drain insertion if unsuccessful.","Mitral valve prolapse is characterized by a mid-systolic click and late systolic murmur, which may be associated with conditions like Marfan syndrome."],"references":["MacDuff\u00a0A,\u00a0Arnold\u00a0A,\u00a0Harvey\u00a0J. Management of spontaneous pneumothorax: British Thoracic Society pleural disease guideline 2010.\u00a0Thorax\u00a02010;65:ii18-ii31. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20696690/","Stuart AG, Williams A. Marfan\u0027s syndrome and the heart.\u00a0Arch Dis Child. 2007;92(4):351-356. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2083669/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74767"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"238"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15018"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15018","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15018"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a343706a-3a3d-40f2-8a15-5d436d1aaead.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a343706a-3a3d-40f2-8a15-5d436d1aaead.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":491,"height":580}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74767","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74767"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T11:24:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-14T11:28:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type"